<TITLE> Houses near Barapukuria coalmine develop cracks </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dinajpur, May 9 (bdnews24.com)  Panicked inhabitants came out on the streets after their houses developed cracks in Kalupara village near Barapukuria coalmine in Dinajpur Thursday night, a UP chairman said Friday. Villagers said that they heard a big bang at 9.30pm Thursday when the walls of their houses developed cracks. About 25 acres of farmland with boro paddies in Balarampur village caved one and a half feet in, said Anwar Hossain Mandal, chairman of Hamidpur Union in Parbatipur. Md Abdul Aziz Khan, managing director of Barapukuria Coal Mining Company, said up to 300 metres of paddy fields in Balarampur subsided up to 22 inches. The land was waterlogged. Khan claimed that earthen walls of only four houses developed cracks. BCMCL formed a committee to investigate the incident. The committee, led by deputy manager of the company Md Kamruzzman, has been asked to submit its report in seven days. bdnews2
